lavery and towards slaves themselves in ways that significantly augment conventional textual accounts.Providing the first interdisciplinary approach to the study of Roman slavery, the volume brings together diverse specialists in history, art history, and archaeology. The contributors engage with questions concerning the slave trade, manumission, slave education, containment and movement, and the use of slaves in the Roman army.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aRomansxMaterial culturevSources. 0aSlaveryzRomexHistoryvSources. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh1 aBruun, Christer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoshel, Sandra R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKampen, Natalie Boymel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeegan, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenski, Noel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMouritsen, Henrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266099140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442660991423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442660991.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK